<div>
	<!-- "article_1060108_body" cached 02/11/2012 at 04:55 PM -->
		<!-- ~verifyCache~ -->
		<div class="slide-view">
	<div id="article-gradient">
		<div id="slide-header">
			<span class="slide-hints"></span>
			<div class="slide-controls">
				<div class="control-previous png-fix">Previous</div>
				<span class="slide-control-numbers"><span class="current-slide">1</span> of 52</span>
				<div class="control-next png-fix">Next</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		
		<div id="slide-content">
							<div class="slide">
										
					<div class="slide-image full-width-slide-image">
						
															<div id="primary-photo" class="media-slot photo-slot" >
									
								  <img alt="Beijingolympicopeningceremony06_original_crop_650x440" height="440" rel="original_file_name:BeijingOlympicOpeningCeremony06_original.jpg" src="http://cdn.bleacherreport.net/images_root/slides/photos/001/899/856/BeijingOlympicOpeningCeremony06_original_crop_650x440.jpg?1328909517" width="650" />								 	
								  <div class="caption-overlay"></div>
																																				</div>
																		</div>

					<div class="slide-description">
													
							
								
													
						<p>Everyone has a bucket list, a collection of places to go or things to do before they leave this Earth.</p><p>But sports fans are a bit more detailed, a tad more specific when they're jotting down a list of places to go.</p><p>Amid the myriad of sports venues around the world, there are 50 that glow brighter than the others.</p><p>Whether they possess immense historical significance or offer unique and breathtaking visuals, these stadiums have set a standard that can't be eclipsed.</p><p>Let's take a peek into 50 sports homes that you need to visit before it's too late.</p><p>Start booking those tickets.</p>

											</div>
				</div>
				<div class="slide-divider"></div>

				
				
				
					<div id="next-slides">
											<div class="slide">
					
						<div class="slide-title">
							<h2>50. AT&T Park, California</h2>
							
						</div>
										
					<div class="slide-image">
						
							
								
									<img alt="Att-park-from-rightfield-with-a-fisheye-night-game_display_image" rel="original_file_name:att-park-from-rightfield-with-a-fisheye-night-game.jpg" src="http://cdn.bleacherreport.net/images_root/slides/photos/001/904/594/att-park-from-rightfield-with-a-fisheye-night-game_display_image.jpg?1328906805" />								

								<br>

								

								<small class="photo-credit"></small>
																		</div>

					<div class="slide-description">
						
							
						
						<p><strong>Capacity</strong>: <em>41,915</em></p><p><strong>Opened</strong>: <em>2000</em></p><p><strong>Teams</strong>: <em>San Francisco Giants</em></p><p>There's arguably nothing more awe-inspiring than hitting a homerun over McCovey Cove, just ask former juiced-up slugger Barry Bonds.</p><p>We'd love to take a walk across history and bask in the ambiance of the epic wall at AT&amp;T Park.</p>

											</div>
				</div>
				<div class="slide-divider"></div>

				
				
											<div class="slide">
					
						<div class="slide-title">
							<h2>49. Wimbledon Centre Court, England</h2>
							
						</div>
										
					<div class="slide-image">
						
							
								
									<img alt="Wimbledon_centre_court_roof_p300609_aeltc_display_image" rel="original_file_name:wimbledon_centre_court_roof_p300609_aeltc.jpg" src="http://cdn.bleacherreport.net/images_root/slides/photos/001/899/861/wimbledon_centre_court_roof_p300609_aeltc_display_image.jpg?1328808268" />								

								<br>

								

								<small class="photo-credit"></small>
																		</div>

					<div class="slide-description">
						
							
						
						<p><strong>Capacity</strong>: <em>15,000</em></p><p><strong>Opened</strong>: <em>1922</em></p><p>Considering it's mostly used for two weeks during the year (3rd annual Grand Slam event), it's curious as to why this court is so significant.</p><p>It's epic proportions seem worthy enough of a visit. We're still trying to lift our jaws off the floor.</p>

											</div>
				</div>
				<div class="slide-divider"></div>

				
				
											<div class="slide">
					
						<div class="slide-title">
							<h2>48. DY Patil Stadium, India</h2>
							
						</div>
										
					<div class="slide-image">
						
							
								
									<img alt="2545217031_cffb72ee70_z_display_image" rel="original_file_name:2545217031_cffb72ee70_z.jpg" src="http://cdn.bleacherreport.net/images_root/slides/photos/001/899/860/2545217031_cffb72ee70_z_display_image.jpg?1328807815" />								

								<br>

								

								<small class="photo-credit"></small>
																		</div>

					<div class="slide-description">
						
							
						
						<p><strong>Capacity</strong>: <em>60,000</em></p><p><strong>Opened</strong>: <em>2008</em></p><p>Teams: Pune Warriors India (IPL)</p><p>Setting a trend for cricket stadium architecture, DY Patil Stadium was the first to have full fledged concert level reinforced music system and the first to have a fabric roof.</p><p>Fans can get a bit rowdy in that beautiful arena.</p>

											</div>
				</div>
				<div class="slide-divider"></div>

				
				
											<div class="slide">
					
						<div class="slide-title">
							<h2>47. The Estadio Alberto J. Armando, Buenos Aires</h2>
							
						</div>
										
					<div class="slide-image">
						
							
								
									<img alt="La_bombonera_display_image" rel="original_file_name:La_Bombonera.jpg" src="http://cdn.bleacherreport.net/images_root/slides/photos/001/899/864/La_Bombonera_display_image.jpg?1328817305" />								

								<br>

								

								<small class="photo-credit"></small>
																		</div>

					<div class="slide-description">
						
							
						
						<p><strong>Capacity</strong>: <em>49,000</em></p><p><strong>Opened</strong>: <em>1940</em></p><p><strong>Teams</strong>: <em>Boca Juniors</em></p><p>Nicknamed La Bombonera, this uniquely-shaped stadium is said to <a href="http://www.pitchcare.com/magazine/la-bombonera-beats.html" target="_blank">beat</a> like a heart as the stands sway during games.</p><p>Intimidation at its finest.</p>

											</div>
				</div>
				<div class="slide-divider"></div>

				
				
											<div class="slide">
					
						<div class="slide-title">
							<h2>46. Murrayfield Stadium, Scotland</h2>
							
						</div>
										
					<div class="slide-image">
						
							
								
									<img alt="3354645106_46bb16ab69_display_image" rel="original_file_name:3354645106_46bb16ab69.jpg" src="http://cdn.bleacherreport.net/images_root/slides/photos/001/899/863/3354645106_46bb16ab69_display_image.jpg?1328809673" />								

								<br>

								

								<small class="photo-credit"></small>
																		</div>

					<div class="slide-description">
						
							
						
						<p><strong>Capacity</strong>: <em>61,730</em></p><p><strong>Opened</strong>: <em>1925</em></p><p><strong>Teams</strong>: <em>Scottish Rugby Union</em></p><p>The largest stadium in Scotland may have decreased its capacity a bit to incorporate the largest permanent big screens in the country, but it's still known best for its large aesthetics.</p><p>A memorable firework display is the appetizer to a feast of beauty.</p>

											</div>
				</div>
				<div class="slide-divider"></div>

				
				
											<div class="slide">
					
						<div class="slide-title">
							<h2>45. Camp Nou, Spain</h2>
							
						</div>
										
					<div class="slide-image">
						
							
								
									<img alt="Camp-nou-stadium_display_image" rel="original_file_name:Camp-Nou-Stadium.jpg" src="http://cdn.bleacherreport.net/images_root/slides/photos/001/899/866/Camp-Nou-Stadium_display_image.jpg?1328821728" />								

								<br>

								

								<small class="photo-credit"></small>
																		</div>

					<div class="slide-description">
						
							
						
						<p><strong>Capacity</strong>: <em>99,354 (96,336 for UEFA)</em></p><p><strong>Opened</strong>: <em>1957</em></p><p><strong>Teams</strong>: <em>FC Barcelona</em></p><p>As we study the most impressive venues around the world, Camp Nou stands tall with its impressive atmosphere and immense size.</p><p>It's the largest stadium in Europe and hosts the world's second-richest club.</p><p>Sounds good to us.</p>

											</div>
				</div>
				<div class="slide-divider"></div>

				
				
											<div class="slide">
					
						<div class="slide-title">
							<h2>44. Estadio Azteca, Mexico</h2>
							
						</div>
										
					<div class="slide-image">
						
							
								
									<img alt="Estadio-azteca-3-0_display_image" rel="original_file_name:estadio-azteca-3-0.jpg" src="http://cdn.bleacherreport.net/images_root/slides/photos/001/901/058/estadio-azteca-3-0_display_image.jpg?1328894439" />								

								<br>

								

								<small class="photo-credit"></small>
																		</div>

					<div class="slide-description">
						
							
						
						<p><strong>Capacity</strong>: <em>104,000</em></p><p><strong>Opened</strong>: <em>1966</em></p><p><strong>Teams</strong>: <em>Club America, Mexico national football team</em></p><p>Not only did it host what's called the <span class="mw-redirect">"Game of the Century" (</span>Italy defeated West Germany 4-3 in 1970 semifinals), but Estadio Azteca's massive capacity makes it the largest stadium in Latin America and the world's largest soccer-only stadium.&nbsp;</p><p>This breathtaking shot from the nosebleed section makes us want to get closer.</p>

